## Outcome of ciprofloxacin and its combinations on body weight
Body weights were measured for each group on the first, third, and seventh days; the percentage of body weight change was calculated and is demonstrated in Fig. 1a. Shigellosis induced by S. boydii AL 17313 had a significant effect on the body weight of mice. The percentage of body weight change in the control group exhibited a gradual increase, whereas the diseased group showed a significant reduction. The difference between the control and diseased groups was statistically significant on day 3 (P < 0.01, d = 3.24, power = 76%) and on day 7 (P < 0.0001, d = 7.94, power = 82%). Treatment groups, including ciprofloxacin alone and in combination with flupentixol, demonstrated weight recovery. There was no statistically significant difference on day 3; however, significance was observed on day 7 (P < 0.01, d = – 2.46, power = 48%).

## Outcome of ciprofloxacin and its combinations on total WBC count
Hematological parameters, such as total WBC count, provide insight into the immune response to antigens and the body’s inflammatory state38. Total WBC counts were determined and compared among groups to find out the curative effect of the treatment groups. In comparison to the control and diseased groups, the total WBC count was significantly elevated in the diseased group (P < 0.0001, d = 10.1, power = 97%), suggesting a heightened inflammatory response caused by shigellosis. As shown in Table 4; Fig. 1b, the ciprofloxacin treatment group had a higher WBC count than the combination treatment group (Cip + Flu), with the difference being statistically significant. This indicates that the combination treatment is more effective (P < 0.05, d = 2.57, power = 85%) in restoring the WBC count to normal levels than ciprofloxacin alone.

## Outcome of ciprofloxacin and its combinations on CRP levels
CRP levels were also determined to evaluate the treatment group’s capability to alleviate it. Elevated CRP levels represented increased inflammatory cytokines in the body39. As shown in Table 4; Fig. 1c, CRP levels were significantly higher in the diseased group compared to the control group (P < 0.0001, d = – 10.22, power = 97%). The combination group had a better alleviation capacity, although the difference was not statistically significant.

## Outcome of ciprofloxacin and its combinations on ESR
Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) test is a diagnostic test that specifies inflammatory conditions within the body arising from several diseases, infections, and tumors. An elevated ESR level indicates the presence of specific inflammatory cytokines and disease progression39. The ESR level determined for every group is summarized in Table 4; Fig. 1d. In comparison between the control group and the diseased group, elevated levels of ESR indicate a higher inflammatory state associated with shigellosis (P < 0.0001, d = -8.43, power = 87%). Treatment groups alleviated inflammatory states at different levels. However, higher ESR levels were found in the ciprofloxacin group compared to the combination group Cip + Flu, indicating that the combination group has a greater capability to reduce the body’s inflammatory condition compared to ciprofloxacin alone, which is statistically significant for Cip + Flu (P < 0.01, d = 3.74, power = 88%).
